description.text:
The model is a single pair of leg mechanisms, based on The Jansen's Strandbeest design. Printed and assembled the mechanism will allow movement of all parts mimicking the movement profile of animal legs.
All of the model's parts are printed in a very simple manner and no supports or rafts are required.
Motion can be achieved manually using a lever or automatically - connecting the drive shaft to an electrical motor.

https://youtu.be/bpCLDusuZ40

Printer:

Prusa i3

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2mm

Infill:

10

Notes:

The "PART_SPREAD".stl includes all the required parts.
It is a very simple print, took me a couple of hours. I printed it on a bed of 20 cm X 20 cm, at its current size it can be printed on a smaller bed. Feel free to scale up or down since all the parts are printed.

Assembly

Assembly is the more complicated part of this mechanism. You can see how all the parts fit together viewing the "ASSEMBLY" files attached (.stl and .stp). The assembly is based on different shafts in a tight fit locking some parts in place and allowing other parts rotation.
Since the tight fits require high precision and most printers have different offsets I would recommend experimenting with the tight fit part's scaling. For this purpose i added a "TIGHT FIT" .stl document separate from the rest of the parts so you can make them bigger or smaller in case assembly doesn't go smooth

description.text:
This is a standard dovetail clamp (Vixen type) I made to adapt a 80mm refractor telescope into a cheap ALT-AZ mount. Despite the mount isn't rigid at all, the connection done by this clamp is pretty sturdy. I recommend to print it at 100% infill as I did. As you can notice looking at the models, I made several pass through holes perpendicularly to the layers of the 3D print in order to transfer the stresses during operation to the threaded rods, thus lowering the load applied in the printed parts.

I also uploaded the NX (Unigraphics) files in .prt format in case you need to modify the dimensions.

Enjoy it!

Idea based on (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:97884), but jazzed up and powered by USB. X3G files provided for Replicator 2 PLA. Bill of materials:
  • 5 Lithophanes (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:229961) customized with the default dimensions (can tweak bottom_padding).
  • Printed lithobox parts (6).
  • High power LED with star shaped heatsink (http://www.adafruit.com/products/518, http://tinyurl.com/ly6twsn or http://tinyurl.com/lv4chvo). Really any bright (~1 watt) LED will do, but it's important that it has a 'wide' beam pattern so that it lights all the lithophanes evenly.
  • microUSB breakout for power (https://www.sparkfun.com/products/12035).
  • M2 x 10mm bolts (2), M2 x 20mm bolts (4), M2 hexnuts (6)
  • Resistor of appropriate value (Use http://ledcalc.com with the parameters from your sourced LED, voltage source @ 5V). Make sure your circuit doesn't go over the max allowed USB current (recommended 100 mA, absolute max 500 mA).
  • USB cable.
    • Update Dec 14, 2014:
    -Expanded M2 clearance holes

Print 5 custom lithophanes (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:229961), using your own image and the default settings. Print all 6 components of lithobox. Suggested settings:
  • all at 0.1 mm layer thickness
  • use helper disks on corners to prevent warping
  • lithobox-mount and lithobox-clamp with supports. Won't be pretty, but it's internal so it doesn't matter too much.
  • optional to save filament: both lithobox-bottom parts, use a custom makerware profile with floor set to 0 to save plastic and print time. The pieces will not have a base layer and will print infill right away, but since the two shells are attached together, it will not make a difference in the final construction.

Goldorak Go !!!
Diffusé entre 1975 et 1977 au Japon Goldorak aura surtout marqué les petits français des années 80. Simple spin off de Mazinger Z, LE déclencheur de la vague mecha au Japon, Goldorak est le symbol de la génération 80 en France. Il fallait donc bien que je m'y attèle, même si évidemment il ne parlera qu'à nous, pauvres "Baguettes" et à quelques autres pays européens.
Pour lui rendre hommage (et donc à son auteur, Go Nagai), je ne pouvais que tenter l'expérience des membres articulés.
Il va donc falloir s'accrocher.
Le Goldorak présenté ici, est un agrandissement en 4x avant impression des pièces en STL et comme si ça ne suffisait pas, il est accompagné de sa soucoupe.suivez le lien:

Notes:

Selon les pièces, il faudra penser à des supports. J'ai essayé d'éviter au maximum, mais pas réussit partout. L'impression est très longue pour certaine (surtout en taille x4). Compter une journée pour un quart de soucoupe.
our la plupart des pièces, il faut imprimer deux fois en utilisant la fonction miroir ( mirror) de CURA.

Un petit coup de marteau pour enfoncer les chevilles dans les pieds

Dans la jambe, derrière le genou, un coup de cuter pour supprimer la cale de l'impression et ensuite ...

... avec un tournevis plat, bouger délicatement le haut de la jambe. Ne pas forcer, mais faire des va et vient légers jusqu'à que ça tourne.

Poncer délicatement la partie du haut de la jambe noir. Vérifier que la partie grise passe bien autour de la partie noir, quelle tourne, mais qu'il y ai encore un peu de frottements.

Poncer encore les parties si nécessaire avant de les emboiter. Mais il faut surtout qu'il y ai encore des frottements. En cas de jeu trop important, plier du papier et faite le glisser entre les pièces, ça marche très bien pour durcir les articulations.

Pour le torse, j'ai laissé les supports d'impression, y a une meilleure prise de la colle.

Penser à couper au cutter le petit support entre la tete et le coup, puis faites des vas et viens légers pour pivoter la tete en avant et en arrière.

Emboiter les deux partie du coup (attention y aura du jeu) un petit bout de papier avant d'emboiter peut être ?

L'épaule est en trois parties (ne pas utiliser de colle). Coller ensuite la partie grise sur l'épaule.

Les supports pour les astirohaches sont trop fragiles. J'ai couper un clou et collé la pointe à la place. Elles doivent rester amovibles pour les transformer. Attention:
Elles sont moches une fois sortie, j'ai donc fait de nouvelles lames pour les fixer au baton.

et oui en x4 un quart de soucoupe prend tout le plateau (et 15h d'impression)

title: 2.5" hard drive enclosure. Tool free and USM standard.

description.text:
The USM standard is a few years old now. It is a standard designed to allow all drives to match with any plug. The USM cases expose the bare SATA port, which plugs into various adaptors (USB3, Thunderbolt, etc).

This enclosure is:
• USM compatible, so it will fit any USM adaptors out there like the Seagate thunderbolt adaptor (Also, perhaps the ubiquitous USB3 - SATA plugs on Ebay. Not sure though).

• Tool free. Able to be printed in a single print run on a 200x200 bed machine. No screws needed. Can be disassembled with bare hands.

• Compatible with any 2.5" drive size up to 9.5mm. Just scale up or down the spacer if needed. Spacer is for 7mm drives by default.

• Has sufficient thickness in the lid to emboss any text you like.

• Includes two base models - one for drives with a metal shield surrounding them (see my SSD example) and one for bare drives. The metal shield is useful as the Seagate Thunderbolt adaptor uses a magnet in its base to hold the drive a bit tighter.

Update: 20/6/17
I added another spacer with a slightly trimmed end for use with metal shields that folds back over the drive. (Eg: the samsung drive example in my photos).

title: Simple Lithography Box with or witout Text

description.text:
A simple Lithography box with 3 variations of text on top (No text, Live Love Laugh, Where there is light there is love). Example Lithophane included with help files.

Easy to replace images or candle inside by just lifting the top of and sliding new images in.

How to make the Lithophanes:

  • Create an square image of 10 cm with a white rim of 0.5 cm on each side. Total should be 11 cm in both directions. If you have Photoshop I created an easy drop in file for you to use with the correct proportions. If you don't have Photoshop you can look at the example file I added to create your own.
  • Add thickness in your prefered 3d program or online converter. The easiest (and free) way I found was to use Cura and to just drag and drop the image in. The most important settings are the width and depth of 11 cm, and a base of 0.5 mm. Also make sure that "Darker is higher" option is set. You can set Height yourself depending on how much contrast you want, and I would recommend not using any smoothing.
  • Now print 4 lithophanes and slide them into the box and you are ready to go.

If you have further improvements or questions, don't be afraid to message me and I will be glad to help you out.

This is my take on e3d v6 heater block sleeve/sock. My very first attempt with casting silicone and very first 3d printed mould that I've designed by myself. I do realize that there are a few existing models on Thingiverse, I decided to make one myself as a challenge for both casting silicone and designing a mould in Fusion 360. It is also much cheaper (in the long run) and much more interesting to create your own silicone sleeves.

It is compatible with the older version of genuine e3d v6 or majority of the e3d v6 clone commonly sold on Aliexpress.

I will occasionally share my creations and 3d printing reviews on my youtube channel if you are interested in my contents/creations you are welcome to subscribe to my channel.

Pouring instructions:

  1. clean up and post-process your the 3d printed parts a little with sandpaper or file.
  2. use a rubber band to secure the side wall. There are a top and bottom side, make sure the wall is oriented correctly.
  3. prepare your high-temperature resistance silicone accordingly.
  4. OPTIONAL: degas the silicone (if you have a vacuum chamber)
  5. pour the silicone until about 1/3 full of the mould.
  6. insert the dummy 3d printed heater block
  7. push the dummy 3d printed heater block into the proper slots
  8. pour some more silicone until the block is completely covered.
  9. close the lid firmly
  10. wait for it to dry.

title: DIY Brass Nut Bushings for X- and Y-Axes

description.text: I am using stainless steel smooth rods (A2/V2A). When I use the standard LM8UU type linear bearings on these rods, the hardened steel balls of the bearings will end up cutting ugly grooves into the rods. Even though I can reduce this problem by rotating the rods by a few degrees around the axis from time to time, I don't like this combination of soft and hard steel. One solution is to use brass bushings instead of the linear steel bearings. Brass on steel has a very low friction coefficient and causes very little abrasive wear. But as it turned out, I could not find any ready made brass bushings around here. So I looked in my garage if I could find any brass objects from which I could make some DIY bushings... And what did I find? A handful of M8 brass nuts! When I bored out the thread with a 8mm drill bit and chamfered the rims, I was amazed how easily the nuts moved on the 8mm smooth rods. So I decided to give it a try and use these DIY bushings on the X- and Y-Axes of the new box-framed Prusa i3 I am building. As I could not find any reference of someone else already having used the same type of simple brass bushings, I had to adapt myself the X- and Y-carriages. The frame for one bushing is simple, as it essentially consists in a nut trap with two holes for a zip tie which retains the nut. The Y-axis was relatively simple. However, my first try of using a separate frame from each of the four bushings was not successful. It turns out that it's not so easy to align the nuts precisely enough. Combining the two bushings from each rod into a one frame made the alignment and mounting of the print bed much easier. Two STL files are included, one for 70mm spacing of the two nuts and the other for 100mm spacing. The corresponding SCAD file is also provided. For the X-axis things are a bit more complicated, as one has to integrate the nut bushing frame into the Prusa i3 source code. The included x-carriage STL files are for MXL, T2.5 and GT2 belts. But since I use MXL belts on my i3, only that STL file has been tested. As my ad-hoc modifications of the original i3 code are rather "quick-and-dirty" and I don't want to copy the whole source code into this project, I have just uploaded a diff-file showing the modifications I made to Prusa's x-carriage.scad, for those who want to know exactly what I did. As to the performance of my new brass nut bushings: The X- and Y-carriages glide at least as easily on my (now finished) i3 as they do on my Mendel which uses LM8UUs. However, when sliding the carriages by hand, I noted that the nut bushings are rather sensitive to pushing/pulling off-center. But since the belts apply their force at the center, the carriages glide very nicely and precisely when moved by the steppers. So far I am quite satisfied with the first prints I did on my new i3. Thus, the brass nut bushings seem to work well. But of course, this is only a first go at it. It remains to be seen how the bushings will perform in the long run... So I'd be quite interested to hear from others who have done some work with these or other DIY brass bushings. Update 2014-02-02: I also uploaded the files for a version of the x-carriage which uses 4 bushings instead of the standard 3. Given the short axial length of a single nut bushings, I think that it makes sense to have two on each rod. Update 2014-02-10: I just realized that I can also use these bushings for non-standard sized smooth rods (i.e. anything other than the usual 8mm or 10mm rods), such as e.g. the nice 9mm rods that can be salvaged from most outdated Epson inkjet printers.

description.text:
Using the ISO standard as described in the attached ThreadTech diagram, I was able to print very usable screw threads using PLA, at 0.2 line thickness.

The ONE adaptation needed is that I had to increase the diameter of the female thread by 0.8mm. This gave me threads that mated with very little resistance (almost zero). I could probably have safely decreased the diameter difference to 0.6mm. Note that at a diameter difference of 0.4mm, I was not able to screw the nut and bolt together. [See my design notes on how this could be improved.]

I did my experiment using a male effective diameter of 3.4cm with a 3mm thread pitch (P). In ISO terms, this is expressed as M34 x 3.0.

I included a screen shot from Blender which shows the profiles of the male and female threads, with the above mentioned spacing of 0.4mm radius (0.8mm diameter). P=3mm in this example.

An additional design component of working threads is that the mating ends of the thread shafts should be "camphered" at 45 degrees. This is equivalent to shaving off the edge of the outermost threads with a 45 degree conical surface. The purpose of the campher is to make the threads of the two parts self-centering, and to align the two parts along the same axis, which will help avoid thread stripping.

Conclusion: Given the diameter spacing adaptation required with printing tolerances with current technology FDM techniques, it would be challenging to get ISO thread diameters to be functional below a male M8 x 1.0.
